Sure! Here's a MATLAB script that simulates the sending and reception of a QPSK payload on a static channel with an EbN0 of 5dB:

```matlab
% Set simulation parameters
numBits = 10000;    % Number of bits to transmit
EbN0dB = 5;         % Eb/N0 in dB
EbN0 = 10^(EbN0dB/10); % Eb/N0 in linear scale
SNRdB = EbN0dB + 10*log10(2); % SNR in dB (QPSK has 2 bits per symbol)
SNR = 10^(SNRdB/10); % SNR in linear scale

% Generate random bit sequence
bits = randi([0,1],1,numBits);

% QPSK modulation
symbols = 2*bits(1:2:end) - 1 + 1j*(2*bits(2:2:end) - 1);

% Add complex Gaussian noise
noise = sqrt(1/(2*SNR))*(randn(1,numBits/2) + 1j*randn(1,numBits/2));
receivedSymbols = symbols + noise;

% QPSK demodulation
receivedBits = zeros(1,numBits);
receivedBits(1:2:end) = real(receivedSymbols) > 0;
receivedBits(2:2:end) = imag(receivedSymbols) > 0;

% Calculate bit error rate
numErrors = sum(bits ~= receivedBits);
bitErrorRate = numErrors/numBits;

% Display results
fprintf('Eb/N0 = %.2f dB\n', EbN0dB);
fprintf('Bit Error Rate = %.4e\n', bitErrorRate);
```

This script generates a random bit sequence and modulates it using QPSK. Complex Gaussian noise is added to the modulated symbols to simulate the channel. The received symbols are then demodulated back to bits. The bit error rate is calculated by comparing the original and received bits.

You can run this script in MATLAB to simulate the QPSK transmission and reception on a static channel with an EbN0 of 5dB. The resulting bit error rate will give you an idea of the performance of the system under the given conditions.

Here is a memcpy() implementation using RT-Thread variable name conventions:

```c
rt_size_t rt_memcpy(void *dst, const void *src, rt_size_t n)
{
    rt_uint8_t *p_dst = (rt_uint8_t *)dst;
    rt_uint8_t *p_src = (rt_uint8_t *)src;
    rt_size_t i;

    for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        *p_dst++ = *p_src++;
    }

    return dst;
}
```

- Use `rt_` as a prefix for variable names 
- Use `rt_size_t` for size/length variables
- Use `rt_uint8_t` for 8-bit unsigned integers

