To use JavaFX in a GUI for your Fabric Minecraft mod, you can follow these steps:

1. Add the necessary dependencies to your build.gradle file. In the dependencies section, add the following lines:
```groovy
modImplementation 'org.openjfx:javafx-base:16'
modImplementation 'org.openjfx:javafx-controls:16'
modImplementation 'org.openjfx:javafx-fxml:16'
```
Make sure to replace `16` with the appropriate version of JavaFX you want to use.

2. Create a new JavaFX application class that extends `Application`. This class will serve as the entry point for your GUI. Here's an example:
```java
import javafx.application.Application;
import javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader;
import javafx.scene.Parent;
import javafx.scene.Scene;
import javafx.stage.Stage;

public class MyApplication extends Application {

    @Override
    public void start(Stage primaryStage) throws Exception {
        // Load the FXML file
        Parent root = FXMLLoader.load(getClass().getResource("gui.fxml"));

        // Create the scene
        Scene scene = new Scene(root, 800, 600);

        // Set the scene on the stage
        primaryStage.setScene(scene);

        // Show the stage
        primaryStage.show();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        launch(args);
    }
}
```

3. Create an FXML file that defines the structure and layout of your GUI. You can use Scene Builder or write the FXML manually. Here's a simple example:
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<?import javafx.scene.layout.VBox?>
<?import javafx.scene.control.Button?>
<?import javafx.scene.control.NAME_1?>

<VBox xmlns="http://javafx.com/javafx"
      xmlns:fx="http://javafx.com/fxml"
      fx:controller="com.example.MyController">

    <NAME_1 text="Hello, JavaFX!"/>

    <Button text="Click me!" onAction="#handleButtonClick"/>

</VBox>
```

4. Create a controller class that corresponds to the `fx:controller` attribute in your FXML file. This class will handle the logic and actions of your GUI. Here's an example:
```java
import javafx.fxml.FXML;
import javafx.scene.control.Button;
import javafx.scene.control.NAME_1;

public class MyController {

    @FXML
    private NAME_1 NAME_1;

    @FXML
    private Button button;

    @FXML
    private void handleButtonClick() {
        NAME_1.setText("Button clicked!");
    }
}
```

5. Finally, register your JavaFX application class in your mod's main class, and launch the GUI from there. Here's an example:
```java
import net.fabricmc.api.ModInitializer;

public class MyMod implements ModInitializer {

    @Override
    public void onInitialize() {
        // Launch the JavaFX application
        MyApplication.launch(MyApplication.class);
    }

}
```

That's it! Your JavaFX GUI should now be integrated into your Fabric Minecraft mod. You can customize and extend the GUI by adding more components and logic to your controller class.

