A NAME_1 is a design pattern that restricts the instantiation of a class to a single instance and provides a global point of access to it. In C++, you can create a NAME_1 class using smart pointers. Here is a simple example using `std::shared_ptr`:

```cpp
#include <memory>
#include <mutex>

class NAME_1 {
public:
    static std::shared_ptr<NAME_1> getInstance() {
        std::call_once(initInstanceFlag, &NAME_1::initSingleton);
        return instance;
    }

    NAME_1(const NAME_1& other) = delete;
    NAME_1& operator=(const NAME_1& other) = delete;

private:
    NAME_1() {}

    static void initSingleton() {
        instance.reset(new NAME_1);
    }

    static std::shared_ptr<NAME_1> instance;
    static std::once_flag initInstanceFlag;
};

// Initialize pointers
std::shared_ptr<NAME_1> NAME_1::instance;
std::once_flag NAME_1::initInstanceFlag;
```

In this code, the `getInstance` method is used to access the single instance of the `NAME_1` class. `std::call_once` is used to guarantee that the instance will be initialized only once, even in the presence of multiple threads.

The copying constructor and assignment operator are both deleted to prevent creating another instance of the `NAME_1` class.

The `std::shared_ptr` manages the memory of the `NAME_1` instance, and it is automatically deallocated when the program ends.

Remember that use of singletons is often considered an anti-pattern because it can make your code harder to test and reason about, so use it with care.

