There are several possible statuses for a thread in NAME_1:

1. New - The thread has been created but not yet started. It is in ready state.
2. Runnable - The thread is running or ready to run. This is the state when the thread is actually executing in the CPU or waiting to get into the CPU.
3. Blocked - The thread is blocked waiting for a monitor lock.
4. Waiting - The thread is waiting for some other resource. For example, it may be waiting for I/O to complete. 
5. Timed Waiting - The thread is waiting for a specified amount of time. For example, it may be waiting in a sleep() call.
6. Terminated - The thread has completed its execution.

You can get the status of a thread using the `getState()` method. For example:

```NAME_1
Thread t = new Thread();

// Prints NEW 
System.out.println(t.getState());

t.start();

// Prints RUNNABLE
System.out.println(t.getState());  

t.join();

// Prints TERMINATED
System.out.println(t.getState());  
```

The `join()` call waits for the thread to finish, which is why we see the TERMINATED state at the end.

You can also use the `isAlive()` method to check if a thread is still running or not.

