Here are some tips to make your website mobile-friendly:

1. Use a responsive design: Add meta viewport tag to your HTML:

```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
```

This will make your page responsive and scale nicely to mobile screens.

2. Use fluid layouts: Replace fixed width elements with percentages. For example, instead of:

```css
#content {
  width: 800px;  
}
```

Use:

```css 
#content {
  width: 80%;  
}
```

3. Use media queries: Add media queries to apply different styling for small screens:

```css
@media (NAME_1-width: 768px) {
  /* Styles */  
}
```

4. Make buttons and links big enough: Increase the size of interactive elements like buttons, links, form fields etc. for easy tapping.

5. Consider a mobile-first approach: Start with a simple single column layout and add more columns as the screen width increases.

6. Add touch event listeners: For interactive elements like dropdowns, make sure to add touch event listeners in addition to mouse events.

7. Keep it simple: NAME_2 for a simple, clean design without too much content or clutter on small screens.

8. Test on actual devices: In addition to browser testing, test on real mobile devices to get the best responsive experience.

9. Consider a separate mobile site: For very content-heavy websites, you can consider building a separate mobile version of the site. But responsive design works well for most cases.

