You can define interface for the data response dynamically in TypeScript like this:

```ts
interface DataResponse<T> {
  success: boolean;
  data: T;
  pagination: Pagination; 
}

type Province = {
  id: number;
  code: string;
  name: string;
  status: string;
  meta: string; 
}

type Address = {
  id: string;
  kkks_id: string;
  province_code: string;
  city_code: string;
  district_code: string;
  village_code: string;
  name: string;
  latitude: number;
  longitude: number;
  zip_code: string;
  address_detail: string;
  is_default: string | null;
  created_at: string;
}

type ProvinceResponse = DataResponse<{
  province: Province[];  
}>

type AddressResponse = DataResponse<{
  address: Address[];  
}>

let provinceResponse: ProvinceResponse = {
  success: true,
  data: {
    province: [/*...*/]
  },
  pagination: { /*...*/ } 
} 

let addressResponse: AddressResponse = {
  success: true,
  data: {
    address: [/*...*/]
  },
  pagination: { /*...*/ } 
}
```

Here we define a generic `DataResponse<T>` interface which represents the data response. We give it a generic type `T` which will be the type of the `data` property.

Then we define `Province` and `Address` types to represent the `province` and `address` data.

Finally, we define `ProvinceResponse` and `AddressResponse` types which extend the generic `DataResponse<T>` interface, giving it the specific `Province` and `Address` types respectively.

So now `provinceResponse` and `addressResponse` have the correct types based on the data they contain.

