Yes, in Spring Boot you can manipulate the response using ResponseFilter. A ResponseFilter allows you to intercept the response before it is written to the client.

For example, you can have a ResponseFilter like this:
```java
@Component
public class MyResponseFilter implements ResponseFilter {
    @Override
    public void doFilter(ServletRequest request, ServletResponse response, FilterChain chain) 
            throws IOException, ServletException {
        HttpServletResponse httpResponse = (HttpServletResponse) response;
        httpResponse.addHeader("My-Header", "Some value");
        chain.doFilter(request, response);
    }
} 
```

This will add a "My-Header" header to all responses.

To register this filter, you need to add it to the filters list in your application.properties:

```
spring.servlet.response.filters=MyResponseFilter 
```

Now all responses from your Spring Boot app will have the "My-Header" header added.

You can perform any manipulation on the HttpServletResponse in the doFilter method - add/remove headers, change content type, modify response body, etc.

